#: ../../H/heatseeker.rst:5
msgid "heatseeker"
msgstr "heatseeker"

#: ../../H/heatseeker.rst:7
msgid "n\\."
msgstr "名詞"

#: ../../H/heatseeker.rst:9
msgid ""
"[IBM] A customer who can be relied upon to buy, without fail, the latest "
"version of an existing product (not quite the same as a member of the "
":ref:`lunatic-fringe`\\). A 1993 example of a heatseeker was someone who, "
"owning a 286 PC and Windows 3.0, went out and bought Windows 3.1 (which "
"offers no worthwhile benefits unless you have a 386). If all customers were "
"heatseekers, vast amounts of money could be made by just fixing some of the "
"bugs in each release (n) and selling it to them as release (n+1). Microsoft "
"in fact seems to have mastered this technique."
msgstr ""
"[IBM]既存製品の最新版を間違いなく必ず買うと当てにできる顧客(\\ :ref:`lunatic-fringe`\\ "
"のメンバーとはやや異なる)。1993年のheatseekerの例は、286 PCとWindows 3.0を所有していながら、Windows "
"3.1(386を持っていない限り何ら価値ある利益を提供しない)を買いに行った人物である。もしすべての顧客がheatseekerだったら、各リリース(n)のバグのいくつかを直してリリース(n+1)として彼らに売るだけで、莫大な金額を稼げるだろう。Microsoftは実際この技術を習得したようである。"
